<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Roofs: PAP Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Complete reference for PAP flags, how to view them on the map, and how to apply them safely.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What are PAP Flags?
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>PAP flags</Bold> are binary properties attached to each cell that tell the engine
        how the cell should behave. Multiple flags can be set on a single cell simultaneously.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Most flags are set automatically by the Auto-Build system when you create buildings.
        However, you can manually apply or remove flags for special effects, mission areas, or
        fine-tuning.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A2A3A" BorderBrush="#4A4A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#B0B0E0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Note:</Run>
                <Run> Not all PAP flags are fully understood or documented. Some may be unused by the engine, or their exact behavior may vary depending on game version. The descriptions below represent the best current understanding.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Viewing PAP Flags on the Map
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The
        <Bold>PAP Flags layer</Bold> lets you preview flagged cells directly on the map.
        Matching cells are now highlighted across the
        <Bold>entire cell area</Bold> , making them
        much easier to identify than the older corner marker display.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Next to the
        <Bold>PAP Flags</Bold> layer toggle, there is also a
        <Bold>multi-select filter dropdown</Bold> . Use this to choose which PAP flags should be
        shown in the overlay.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Filter Behaviour
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                If you select a single flag such as
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> , only cells containing
                that flag are highlighted.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                If you select multiple flags such as
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> and
                <Bold>RoofExists</Bold> , only cells containing
                <Bold>all selected flags</Bold>
                are highlighted.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                If no specific filter flags are selected, the overlay shows all cells that have
                any PAP flags set.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        When the PAP Flags layer is visible, you can still
        <Bold>double-click</Bold> a highlighted
        cell to open the
        <Bold>Cell Flags Editor</Bold> for that exact cell.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        PAP Flag Reference
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Shadow Boxes
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Defines shadows for sloped roofs. Used to create realistic shadow casting on angled surfaces.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Usage:</Bold> Applied automatically by the engine on sloped RF4 tiles. Rarely needs
        manual setting.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Reflective
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Surface reflects light, creating a wet or shiny appearance.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Status:</Bold> Possibly unused by the final engine. May have been intended for wet-look
        tiles but not fully implemented.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Hidden (Indoor Cell)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Cell is an
        <Bold>interior cell</Bold> and has a ceiling above it. The player is inside a
        structure.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Usage:</Bold> Automatically set by the Auto-Build system on warehouse interiors. This
        tells the engine to render the interior view and hide the sky/outdoor elements.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Critical:</Bold> Required for warehouse buildings to function correctly. Without this
        flag, warehouse interiors will not render properly.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        SinkSquare
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Lowers the floor square to create a curb or step-down effect.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Usage:</Bold> Used for creating curbs, gutters, or small elevation changes within
        a cell. The exact lowering amount may be engine-defined.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        SinkPoint
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Player sinks into the tile (originally intended for water tiles).
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Status:</Bold> Probably unused in the final game. Was likely intended to make the
        player sink when standing in water, but this behavior may not be fully implemented.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        NoUpper
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Controls which side of a stepped edge gets deformed.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Status:</Bold> Probably unused. May have been intended for edge-smoothing on height
        transitions but not fully implemented.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        NoGo
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Player
        <Bold>cannot enter</Bold> this cell. Functions the same as a No Go Zone in the
        mission file.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Status:</Bold> Unused in map files. This is now handled in Mission (UCM) files.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        RoofExists
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Tells the engine the player should stand on the
        <Bold>roof altitude height</Bold> rather
        than the terrain height.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Usage:</Bold> Automatically set by the Auto-Build system on non-warehouse buildings.
        This is the key flag that makes roof surfaces walkable.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Critical:</Bold> If you manually set a cell altitude (for example, for a bridge), you
        <Bold>must</Bold> also set the RoofExists flag, otherwise the player will fall through.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Warehouse Note:</Bold> Do
        <Bold>not</Bold> use RoofExists on warehouse interiors.
        Warehouses use RF4 tiles for floors and keep this flag off.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Zone Flags (Zone 0 – Zone 7)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Eight zone flags that function the same as zone flags in the Mission Editor. These can be
        used to create specific areas for mission event trigger points.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Usage:</Bold> Unused in map files. These are now set in Mission (UCM) files.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Flat Roof
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Indicates the cell has a roof, but it is not sloped.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Status:</Bold> Probably unused. The engine likely determines flat vs. sloped roofs
        from RF4 tile corner heights rather than this flag.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Water
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Marks the tile as water. Sets sink behavior around the tile and updates the water level
        rendering.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Bold>Status:</Bold> Probably unused or partially implemented. The game may not fully
        support dynamic water tile behavior defined via PAP flags.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Applying PAP Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        You can apply PAP flags to cells using the
        <Bold>Drag Area</Bold> tool. This allows you
        to bulk-edit rectangular areas of the map, then verify the result immediately using the
        highlighted PAP Flags overlay on the canvas.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Tri-State Flag Controls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Each PAP flag checkbox now has three states so repeated drag operations do not destroy
        existing flags unintentionally.
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Checked</Bold> — apply this flag to the selection
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Filled</Bold> — leave this flag unchanged on the selection
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Unchecked</Bold> — remove this flag from the selection
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        By default, flags start in the
        <Bold>Filled</Bold> state.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Step-by-Step
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                In the
                <Bold>PAP Flags</Bold> section of the Roofs tab, choose which flags you want
                to set, leave unchanged, or remove.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the
                <Bold>Drag Area</Bold> button. Your cursor changes to indicate flag
                painting mode.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                On the map canvas,
                <Bold>click and drag</Bold> to define a rectangular area.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Release the mouse button. All cells in the selected rectangle are updated according
                to the tri-state checkboxes.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Right-click</Bold> to exit flag painting mode.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/roofs_pap_flags.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: PAP Flags panel showing tri-state flag controls, Drag Area button, and the map overlay used to highlight cells matching the current PAP flag filter
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> Drag Area no longer blindly replaces the full flag byte. Checked flags are added, unchecked flags are removed, and filled flags are left untouched. This allows multiple drag passes without accidentally clearing other PAP flags.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Flag Combinations
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Non-Warehouse Rooftops
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>RoofExists</Bold> +
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> (if under another structure)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="16,2,0,6">
        Standard combination for house roofs. RoofExists makes it walkable; Hidden is added if
        the roof is enclosed by taller buildings.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Warehouse Interiors
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> only (no RoofExists)
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="16,2,0,6">
        Warehouses use RF4 tiles for floors, so RoofExists is not needed. Hidden tells the engine
        to render the interior view.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Tips
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>RoofExists</Bold> and
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> are the most important flags for
                normal building construction. The Auto-Build system handles these automatically.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Zone flags</Bold> are unused in map files. These were replaced with zones in mission files.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>NoGo</Bold> is not used in map files. This is now handled in Mission (UCM) files.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                If a flag's purpose is unclear or marked "probably unused," it is safe to ignore it.
                Focus on
                <Bold>RoofExists</Bold> ,
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> ,
                <Bold>NoGo</Bold> , and
                <Bold>Zone flags</Bold> — these are the most reliable and well-understood.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Flags can be applied outside of walkables or buildings. For example, you can create
                elevated bridges using cell altitudes plus RoofExists without any building facets.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Use the
                <Bold>PAP flag filter dropdown</Bold> beside the layer toggle to isolate
                specific flag combinations on the map. This is especially useful when checking only
                <Bold>Hidden</Bold> cells, only
                <Bold>RoofExists</Bold> cells, or cells that must
                contain both.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
